{"title_page": "H-Net", "text_new": "{{Infobox website\n| name = H-Net\n| logo = Image:HNet Logo with tag.png\n| logo_size = <!-- default 250px -->\n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = <!-- or: | logocaption =  -->\n| screenshot = \n| collapsible = <!-- set as \"on\", \"y\", etc, otherwise omit/leave blank -->\n| collapsetext = <!-- collapsible area's heading (default \"Screenshot\"); omit/leave blank if collapsible not set -->\n| background = <!-- for collapsetext heading; default grey (gainsboro) -->\n| screenshot_size = <!-- default 300px -->\n| screenshot_alt = \n| caption = \n| url = {{URL|https://networks.h-net.org}}\n| commercial = No\n| type = \n| registration = \n| language = English\n| num_users = \n| content_license = <!-- or: | content_licence = -->\n| programming_language = \n| owner = \n| author = \n| editor = <!-- or: | editors = -->\n| launch_date = {{start date and age|March 25, 1993|df=no}}\n| revenue = \n| alexa = <!-- {{increase}} {{steady}} {{decrease}} [http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/example.com ##] (US/Global MM/YYYY) -->\n| current_status = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''H-Net Humanities and Social Sciences Online''' is an international interdisciplinary organization of scholars and teachers dedicated to developing the educational potential of the Internet and the World Wide Web. It has become an \u201cInternational, interdisciplinary network of scholars communicating and sharing resources through a variety of interactive media.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.h-net.org/about/press/oah/peter.html|title=H-Net: Its Past, Present, and Future|last=Knupfer|first=Peter|date=|work=OAH Newsletter|access-date=}}</ref> It is made up of nearly 200 discipline-specific networks that host moderated scholarly discussion, announcements, reviews, formal and informal publications and other scholarly digital content. In addition to dedicated networks, H-Net services include the H-Net Job Guide, H-Net Reviews, H-Announce, the H-Net Book Channel, and the new H-Net journal services. Individual networks are edited and moderated by teams of volunteer editors who are scholars in the network\u2019s subject field.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://networks.h-net.org/node/513/pages/1301/about|title=About H-Net {{!}} H-Net|website=networks.h-net.org|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref> Each network is required to have an advisory board and a staff of online editors. Included in the staff are the positions of the Vice President of Networks, the Vice President of Teaching, and the Vice President of Research and Publications. Elections for the H-Net Executive council occur on an annual basis and are run by the President of Networks. The executive committee is composed of seven representatives, the Executive Director, the Associate Directors, and a treasurer and secretary are appointed.<ref name=\":0\" /> H-Net upholds the goal of maintaining open access scholarly resources. This includes the internationalization of resources to create global accessibility.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.historians.org/publications-and-directories/perspectives-on-history/may-1995/h-net-and-the-internationalization-of-scholarship|title=H-Net and the Internationalization of Scholarship {{!}} Perspectives on History {{!}} AHA|website=www.historians.org|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n\nH-Net is hosted by the Department of History at [[Michigan State University]], but H-Net officers, editors, and subscribers come from all over the globe.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://history.msu.edu/h-net-celebrates-20-years-at-msu/|title=MSU History Department|last=University|first=Michigan State|language=en|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n\n== History of H-Net ==\n'''H-Net: Humanities & Social Sciences Online''' was founded in 1993 by [[Richard J. Jensen|Richard Jensen]], a history professor at the [[University of Illinois at Chicago|University of Illinois - Chicago]]. He was assisted by Wendy Plotkin (a graduate student at the University of Illinois) and James Mott (a PhD of the University of Illinois). H-Net began in the form of a [[LISTSERV]], users could subscribe to groups or \u201clists\u201d and receive notifications in their in-boxes. This platform connected scholars through their in-boxes and made use of the new uses of e-mail. \u00a0\n\nThe earliest lists included: H-Urban, H-Women, H-Holocaust, H-Diplo, H-CivWar, H-Law, H-LatAm, H-South, H-Rural, H-Amstdy, H-Ethnic, H-Albion, H-Teach, H-Judaic, H-OIEAHC (later renamed H-Early-America), H-Film, H-Rhetor, H-Labor, and H-Pol.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://networks.h-net.org/hnet25|title=H-Net 25th Anniversary Crossroads {{!}} H-Net|website=networks.h-net.org|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref> The largest list at the time was HOLOCAUS (later renamed H-Holocaust), with 290 subscribers.\n\nIn 1994, H-Net created its first formal governance structure and elected an executive committee with Richard Jensen as the first Executive Director. H-Net's governance structure consisted of seven elected officers and nine elected council members <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.historians.org/publications-and-directories/perspectives-on-history/may-2007/h-net-digital-discussion-for-historians|title=H-Net: Digital Discussion for Historians {{!}} Perspectives on History {{!}} AHA|website=www.historians.org|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref> This is also the year that H-Net began technology training workshops specifically for the humanities as a part of an [[National Endowment for the Humanities|NEH]] project aimed at introducing scholars to digital humanities and training them to use the internet as a tool.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web |url=http://members.aol.com/dann01/whatis.html |title=Internet's Republic of Letters: H-Net for Scholars |author=Richard Jensen |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000903084512/http://members.aol.com/dann01/whatis.html |archive-date=2000-09-03 |website= |access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n\nThe home office of H-Net moved to Michigan State University's History Department in 1995. The organization held conferences, in conjunction with the [[American Historical Association|AHA]], for all the editors of H-Net in 1995 and again in 1996. H-Net received grants from the National Endowment for the Humanities and the Japanese Foundation (Tokyo); some networks were endorsed by or affiliated with either home campuses or related organizations.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nIn 1996, H-Net took on 4 staffers along with a variety of student helpers at Michigan State University.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nIn 1997, MSU appointed its history Professor Mark Kornbluh as Executive Director, and founded MATRIX: MSU's Humanities Technology Center. Kornbluh also helped establish the constitution and bylaws for the organization.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=McGrath|first=Eileen L.|last2=Metz|first2=Winifred Fordham|last3=Rutledge|first3=John B.|title=H-Net Book Reviews: Enhancing Scholarly Communication with Technology |journal=College & Research Libraries |volume=66 |issue=1 |pages=8\u201319 |date=Jan 2005 |issn=2150-6701 |language=en-US |doi=10.5860/crl.66.1.8|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nWhile its core activity began with a series of field-based, edited email discussion groups that expanded into \u201cnetworks,\u201d each with their own web presence, mission, and intellectual activities, over time H-Net has developed to become a major resource for the training of new scholars.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nH-Net successfully received its non-profit filing endorsement from the Michigan Department of Labor and Economic Growth on 25 June 2001.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://networks.h-net.org/system/files/contributed-files/articles08.pdf|title=Restated Articles of Incorporation \u2013 Non-Profit for H-Net: Humanities and Social Sciences Online|last=|first=|date=|work=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2005 Peter Knupfer was appointed Executive Director after serving as Associate Director and second-in-command for four years. He had been recruited in 2000 by Mark Kornbluh and relocated from Kansas State University to Michigan State University. The duration of Knupfer's term of service as Executive Director was from January 2005 to December 2019.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\"Sara Tucker|first=H.-Net President\" <tuckpres@mail h-net msu edu>|date=2005-03-14|title=INTRODUCING NEW EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR, OFFICERS|url=https://lists.h-net.org/cgi-bin/logbrowse.pl?trx|journal=H-announce}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, H-Net switched platforms from email LISTSERV to a [[Drupal]]-based online commons, allowing both interactivity and online scholarly publications. The discussion log archives from 1994-2012 remain publicly available.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lists.h-net.org/cgi-bin/logbrowse.pl|title=H-Net Discussion Networks -|website=lists.h-net.org|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 H-Net celebrated its 25th anniversary as an organization and held the #HNet25 campaign both on social media and across the Commons. This created the \u201cH-Net 25 Crossroads\u201d,<ref name=\":5\" /> housing the anniversary archive project,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://networks.h-net.org/node/1134508/pages/1549172/mining-h-net-logs|title=Mining the H-Net Logs {{!}} H-Net 25th Anniversary Crossroads {{!}} H-Net|website=networks.h-net.org|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref> and a timeline of the H-Net networks.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== The H-Net Commons ==\n'''The H-Net Commons''', the web home of H-Net: Humanities & Social Sciences Online, is a robust Drupal-based content management platform that serves as the foundation for what many have called H-Net 2.0. The Commons is now home to 180 free online communities (Networks) edited by around 300 volunteer field experts worldwide with approximately 200,000 subscribers, each network overseen by an advisory board of experts.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe H-Net Commons Platform enables users to:\n\n* post images, audio, video, and text\n* exchange discussion messages and receive them via email if they wish\n* view users\u2019 profiles\n* customize subscribed network content using a \"My H-Net\" content widget\n* deliver pages via [[RSS|RSS feeds]] to their mailboxes or feed readers\n* create blogs and customize pages of links and other content\n* create content-based projects (image archives, a series of podcasts, a syllabus commons, etc.)\n* use private planning space for network editorial teams\n* create content through a common web-based interface\n* search for material across H-Net that has been categorized and tagged by editors and users for easy retrieval, bookmarking, and saving dynamic searches to My H-Net <ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===List of H-Net Commons Networks===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! A - C !! D - H !! I - N !! O - S !! T - Z\n|-\n|  [https://networks.h-net.org/h-1960s H-1960s] || [https://networks.h-net.org/h-dc H-DC] || [https://networks.h-net.org/h-ideas H-Ideas] || [https://networks.h-net.org/h-oralhist H-OralHist]  || [https://networks.h-net.org/h-tah TAH]\n|-\n| [https://networks.h-net.org/h-adjunct H-Adjunct] || [https://networks.h-net.org/h-death H-Death] || [https://networks.h-net.org/h-intel H-Intel] || [https://networks.h-net.org/h-pcaaca H-PCAACA] || [https://networks.h-net.org/h-teach H-Teach]\n|-\n| [https://networks.h-net.org/h-afrarts H-AfrArts] || [https://networks.h-net.org/h-decol H-Decol] || [https://networks.h-net.org/h-islamart H-IslamArt] || [https://networks.h-net.org/h-peace H-Peace] || [https://networks.h-net.org/h-teachpol H-TeachPol]\n|-\n| [https://networks.h-net.org/h-africa H-Africa] || [https://networks.h-net.org/h-democracy H-Democracy] || [https://networks.h-net.org/h-islaminafrica H-IslamInAfrica] || [https://networks.h-net.org/h-pennsylvania H-Pennsylvania] || [https://networks.h-net.org/h-texas H-Texas]\n|-\n| [https://networks.h-net.org/h-afrlitcine H-AfrLitCine] || [https://networks.h-net.org/h-demog H-Demog] || [https://networks.h-net.org/h-italiandiaspora H-ItalianDiaspora] || [https://networks.h-net.org/h-pentecostalism 