{"title_page": "The Living Return", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Living Return\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Swing Out Sister]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = September 1994\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 72:33\n| label      = [[Fontana Records]]\n| producer   = Ray Hayden, Swing Out Sister\n| prev_title = [[Get in Touch with Yourself]]\n| prev_year  = 1992\n| next_title = [[Best of Swing Out Sister]]\n| next_year  = 1996\n}}\n\n'''''The Living Return''''' is the title of the fourth studio album by the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[pop music|pop]] group [[Swing Out Sister]]. It was released in September 1994 on [[Fontana Records]].\n\n==Charts==\nAlthough this was the first studio album by the group that failed to reach the [[UK Albums Chart]], the lead single, \"[[La-La (Means I Love You)]]\", peaked at #37 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>[https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/Melody%20Of%20Love%20%28Wanna%20Be%20Loved%29 Official Charts Company info] OfficialCharts.com. Retrieved 8 April 2009.</ref> This song is a [[cover version]] of the 1968 hit by [[The Delfonics]] and appeared on the soundtrack of the film ''[[Four Weddings and a Funeral]]''. \"Better Make It Better\" was also released as a single, although it did not make the music charts in either the UK or the US. The song \"Mama Didn't Raise No Fool\" was featured on the [[United States|American]] [[Cable television in the United States|basic cable]] and [[Direct-broadcast satellite|satellite television]] [[Television network|network]], [[Disney Channel]].\n\n==Reviews==\n''[[NME|New Musical Express]]'' magazine gave ''The Living Return'' an 8 out of 10 rating in its 17 September 1994 issue, saying that the album \"...sounds divine, a glissando of strings and things, an aural bath for the ears.\"<ref name=\"SOS\">[http://www.swingoutsister.com/albums/albums/living_return.htm Reviews for ''The Living Return''] SwingOutSister.com. Retrieved 8 April 2009.</ref> [[Q (magazine)|''Q'' magazine]] also spoke favourably of the album, mentioning that\t\"SOS have an ear for a snappy arrangements and a mature lightness of touch as they gently echo [[Miles Davis]], [[Weather Report]] and the whole modish Afro era.\"<ref name=\"SOS\"/> It rated the album with four stars and an \"excellent\" rating.\n\n==Track listing==\n'''CD and cassette version'''\n:1. \"Better Make It Better\" - 6:53 <small> ([[Andy Connell]]/[[Corinne Drewery]]) </small>\n:2. \"Don't Let Yourself Down\" - 4:42 <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery) </small>\n:3. \"Ordinary People\" - 6:22 <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery) </small>\n:4. \"Mama Didn't Raise No Fool\" - 5:11 <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery) </small>\n:5. \"Don't Give Up On A Good Thing\" - 3:44 <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery/Derick Johnson/Tim Cansfield) </small>\n:6. \"Making the Right Move\" - 10:32 <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery) </small>\n:7. \"[[La-La (Means I Love You)]]\" - 4:52 <small> ([[Thom Bell|T. Bell]]/W. Hart) </small>\n:8. \"Feel Free\" - 5:06 <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery) </small>\n:9. \"Stop and Think It Over\" - 6:03 <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery) </small>\n:10. \"That's the Way It Goes\" - 4:42 <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery/D. Johnson/T. Cansfield) </small>\n:11. \"All in Your Mind\" - 4:15 <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery) </small>\n:12. \"O Pesadelo Dos Autores\" - 5:26 <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery/M. White/A. Moreira/R. Werneck/T. M. C. Reis/[[Stevie Wonder|S. Wonder]]/S. Moy/H. Cosby/I. Lins/V. Martins/A. De Oliveira/H. Hancock/B. Maupin/Burick) </small>\n:13. \"Low Down Dirty Business\" - 5:19 <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery/D. Johnson/T. Cansfield) </small>\n\n*The song \"O Pesadelo Dos Autores\" features a medley of the songs:\n\n#\"Brazilian Rhyme\" - [[Earth, Wind & Fire]]\n#:<small>From the 1977 album \"[[All 'N All]]\" ([[Maurice White]]) </small> <ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Earth-Wind-Fire-Fantasy-Brazilian-Rhyme-Interlude/release/1490759 Earth Wind & Fire] Discogs.com. Retrieved 9 April 2009.</ref>\n#\"Celebration Suite\" - [[Return to Forever]]\n#:<small>From the 1975 album \"[[No Mystery]]\" ([[Airto Moreira]]) </small> <ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Various-The-Beat-Of-Brazil/release/793556 Airto Moreira] Discogs.com. Retrieved 9 April 2009.</ref>\n#\"Come with Me\" - [[Tania Maria]]\n#:<small>From the 1982 album \"Come with Me\" (Regina Werneck, Tania Maria Correa Reis) </small> <ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Tania-Maria-Come-With-Me/release/784110 Tania Maria] Discogs.com. Retrieved 9 April 2009.</ref>\n#\"[[My Cherie Amour (song)|My Cherie Amour]]\" - [[Stevie Wonder]]\n#:<small>From the 1969 album \"[[My Cherie Amour (album)|My Cherie Amour]]\" (Stevie Wonder, [[Sylvia Moy]], [[Henry Cosby]]) </small> <ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Stevie-Wonder-My-Cherie-Amour-Sunny/release/1465693 Stevie Wonder] Discogs.com. Retrieved 9 April 2009.</ref>\n#\"The Smiling Hour\" - Kalima\n#:<small>From the 1984 single \"The Smiling Hour/Flyaway\" ([[Ivan Lins]], Victor Martins, Aloysio de Oliveira) </small> <ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Kalima-The-Smiling-Hour/release/466892 Kalima] Discogs.com. Retrieved 9 April 2009.</ref>\n#\"Butterfly\" - [[Herbie Hancock]]\n#:<small>From the 1974 album \"[[Thrust (album)|Thrust]]\" (Herbie Hancock, [[Bennie Maupin]]) </small> <ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Herbie-Hancock-Thrust/release/870803 Herbie Hancock] Discogs.com. Retrieved 9 April 2009.</ref>\n\nA limited edition \"edits\" version was also available featuring edited versions of six tracks from the album.\n\n==Personnel==\n;Swing Out Sister \n* [[Corinne Drewery]] \u2013 lead vocals, arrangements\n* [[Andy Connell]] \u2013 keyboards, arrangements\n\n;Additional Musicians\n* Danny Gluckstein \u2013 programming \n* Tim Cansfield \u2013 guitars (1-6, 8-13)\n* Matt Backer \u2013 guitars (7)\n* [[52nd Street (band)|Derrick Johnson]] \u2013 bass guitar \n* Myke Wilson \u2013 drums, [[timbales]] solo (12)\n* [[Kalima (band)|Chris Manis]] \u2013 percussion\n* Gary Plumley \u2013 saxophone, flute \n* [[Richard Edwards (musician)|Richard Edwards]] \u2013 trombone \n* [[John Thirkell]] \u2013 trumpet, flugelhorn\n* Derek Green \u2013 backing vocals \n* Erica Harrold \u2013 backing vocals \n* Sylvia Mason-James \u2013 backing vocals\n\n===Production===\n* Ray Hayden \u2013 producer (1-6, 8-13)\n* Swing Out Sister \u2013 co-producer (1-6, 8-13), producer (7)\n* Mark McGuire \u2013 engineer, mixing \n* Jamie Cullam \u2013 assistant engineer \n* Luke Gifford \u2013 assistant engineer \n\n;Studios\n* Recorded at Opaz Studios and [[Air Studios|Strongroom]] (London, UK).\n* Mixed at Strongroom and [[Metropolis Group|Metropolis Studios]] (London, UK).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Swing Out Sister}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Living Return,The}}\n[[Category:1994 albums]]\n[[Category:Swing Out Sister albums]]\n[[Category:Fontana Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Living Return\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Swing Out Sister]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = September 1994\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 72:33\n| label      = [[Fontana Records]]\n| producer   = Ray Hayden, Swing Out Sister\n| prev_title = [[Get in Touch with Yourself]]\n| prev_year  = 1992\n| next_title = [[Best of Swing Out Sister]]\n| next_year  = 1996\n}}\n\n'''''The Living Return''''' is the title of the fourth studio album by the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[pop music|pop]] group [[Swing Out Sister]]. It was released in September 1994 on [[Fontana Records]].\n\n==Charts==\nAlthough this was the first studio album by the group that failed to reach the [[UK Albums Chart]], the lead single, \"[[La-La (Means I Love You)]]\", peaked at #37 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>[https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/Melody%20Of%20Love%20%28Wanna%20Be%20Loved%29 Official Charts Company info] OfficialCharts.com. Retrieved 8 April 2009.</ref> This song is a [[cover version]] of the 1968 hit by [[The Delfonics]] and appeared on the soundtrack of the film ''[[Four Weddings and a Funeral]]''. \"Better Make It Better\" was also released as a single, although it did not make the music charts in either the UK or the US. The song \"Mama Didn't Raise No Fool\" was featured on the [[United States|American]] [[Cable television in the United States|basic cable]] and [[Direct-broadcast satellite|satellite television]] [[Television network|network]], [[Disney Channel]].\n\n==Reviews==\n''[[NME|New Musical Express]]'' magazine gave ''The Living Return'' an 8 out of 10 rating in its 17 September 1994 issue, saying that the album \"...sounds divine, a glissando of strings and things, an aural bath for the ears.\"<ref name=\"SOS\">[http://www.swingoutsister.com/albums/albums/living_return.htm Reviews for ''The Living Return''] SwingOutSister.com. Retrieved 8 April 2009.</ref> [[Q (magazine)|''Q'' magazine]] also spoke favourably of the album, mentioning that\t\"SOS have an ear for a snappy arrangements and a mature lightness of touch as they gently echo [[Miles Davis]], [[Weather Report]] and the whole modish Afro era.\"<ref name=\"SOS\"/> It rated the album with four stars and an \"excellent\" rating.\n\n==Track listing==\n'''CD and cassette version'''\n:1. \"Better Make It Better\" - (6:53) <small> ([[Andy Connell]]/[[Corinne Drewery]]) </small>\n:2. \"Don't Let Yourself Down\" - (4:42) <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery) </small>\n:3. \"Ordinary People\" - (6:22) <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery) </small>\n:4. \"Mama Didn't Raise No Fool\" - (5:11) <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery) </small>\n:5. \"Don't Give Up On A Good Thing\" - (3:44) <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery/Derick Johnson/Tim Cansfield) </small>\n:6. \"Making the Right Move\" - (10:32) <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery) </small>\n:7. \"[[La-La (Means I Love You)]]\" - (4:52) <small> ([[Thom Bell|T. Bell]]/W. Hart) </small>\n:8. \"Feel Free\" - (5:06) <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery) </small>\n:9. \"Stop and Think It Over\" - (6:03) <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery) </small>\n:10. \"That's the Way It Goes\" - (4:42) <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery/D. Johnson/T. Cansfield) </small>\n:11. \"All in Your Mind\" - (4:15) <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery) </small>\n:12. \"O Pesadelo Dos Autores\" - (5:26) <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery/M. White/A. Moreira/R. Werneck/T. M. C. Reis/[[Stevie Wonder|S. Wonder]]/S. Moy/H. Cosby/I. Lins/V. Martins/A. De Oliveira/H. Hancock/B. Maupin/Burick) </small>\n:13. \"Low Down Dirty Business\" - (5:19) <small> (A. Connell/C. Drewery/D. Johnson/T. Cansfield) </small>\n\n*The song \"O Pesadelo Dos Autores\" features a medley of the songs:\n\n#\"Brazilian Rhyme\" - [[Earth, Wind & Fire]]\n#:<small>From the 1977 album \"[[All 'N All]]\" ([[Maurice White]]) </small> <ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Earth-Wind-Fire-Fantasy-Brazilian-Rhyme-Interlude/release/1490759 Earth Wind & Fire] Discogs.com. Retrieved 9 April 2009.</ref>\n#\"Celebration Suite\" - [[Return to Forever]]\n#:<small>From the 1975 album \"[[No Mystery]]\" ([[Airto Moreira]]) </small> <ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Various-The-Beat-Of-Brazil/release/793556 Airto Moreira] Discogs.com. Retrieved 9 April 2009.</ref>\n#\"Come with Me\" - [[Tania Maria]]\n#:<small>From the 1982 album \"Come with Me\" (Regina Werneck, Tania Maria Correa Reis) </small> <ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Tania-Maria-Come-With-Me/release/784110 Tania Maria] Discogs.com. Retrieved 9 April 2009.</ref>\n#\"[[My Cherie Amour (song)|My Cherie Amour]]\" - [[Stevie Wonder]]\n#:<small>From the 1969 album \"[[My Cherie Amour (album)|My Cherie Amour]]\" (Stevie Wonder, [[Sylvia Moy]], [[Henry Cosby]]) </small> <ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Stevie-Wonder-My-Cherie-Amour-Sunny/release/1465693 Stevie Wonder] Discogs.com. Retrieved 9 April 2009.</ref>\n#\"The Smiling Hour\" - Kalima\n#:<small>From the 1984 single \"The Smiling Hour/Flyaway\" ([[Ivan Lins]], Victor Martins, Aloysio de Oliveira) </small> <ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Kalima-The-Smiling-Hour/release/466892 Kalima] Discogs.com. Retrieved 9 April 2009.</ref>\n#\"Butterfly\" - [[Herbie Hancock]]\n#:<small>From the 1974 album \"[[Thrust (album)|Thrust]]\" (Herbie Hancock, [[Bennie Maupin]]) </small> <ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Herbie-Hancock-Thrust/release/870803 Herbie Hancock] Discogs.com. Retrieved 9 April 2009.</ref>\n\nA limited edition \"edits\" version was also available featuring edited versions of six tracks from the album.\n\n==Personnel==\n;Swing Out Sister \n* [[Corinne Drewery]] \u2013 lead vocals, arrangements\n* [[Andy Connell]] \u2013 keyboards, arrangements\n\n;Additional Musicians\n* Danny Gluckstein \u2013 programming \n* Tim Cansfield \u2013 guitars (1-6, 8-13)\n* Matt Backer \u2013 guitars (7)\n* [[52nd Street (band)|Derrick Johnson]] \u2013 bass guitar \n* Myke Wilson \u2013 drums, [[timbales]] solo (12)\n* [[Kalima (band)|Chris Manis]] \u2013 percussion\n* Gary Plumley \u2013 saxophone, flute \n* [[Richard Edwards (musician)|Richard Edwards]] \u2013 trombone \n* [[John Thirkell]] \u2013 trumpet, flugelhorn\n* Derek Green \u2013 backing vocals \n* Erica Harrold \u2013 backing vocals \n* Sylvia Mason-James \u2013 backing vocals\n\n===Production===\n* Ray Hayden \u2013 producer (1-6, 8-13)\n* Swing Out Sister \u2013 co-producer (1-6, 8-13), producer (7)\n* Mark McGuire \u2013 engineer, mixing \n* Jamie Cullam \u2013 assistant engineer \n* Luke Gifford \u2013 assistant engineer \n\n;Studios\n* Recorded at Opaz Studios and [[Air Studios|Strongroom]] (London, UK).\n* Mixed at Strongroom and [[Metropolis Group|Metropolis Studios]] (London, UK).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Swing Out Sister}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Living Return,The}}\n[[Category:1994 albums]]\n[[Category:Swing Out Sister albums]]\n[[Category:Fontana Records albums]]\n", "name_user": "Joshuadejohnson", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Living_Retu